<font color="#FF0000">A VERY HUMAN PROCESS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 10 21:23:43 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Humming Eagle,<br><br>
It is ironic, but may Vietnam Veterans were turned into &quot;old men&quot; well before their time. PTSD, the underlying disorder with which many struggle day by day, is the very human, but continually debilitating, reaction to their experiences in the War. My diagnosois of PTSD came as a shock, but in retrospect, was the best thing that could have happened. For a while it was just a name. It now has taken on form and meaning, a thing that can be understood and managed.<br><br>
Part of the process is redefining myself. &quot;Tuwe miye he, Who am I?&quot; is at the core. Loss of self and loss of place in life are some of the barriers that are faced. <br><br>
The way to &quot;Tuwe miye he, Who am I?&quot; that you relate is very meaningful. &quot;Ta ta iciya wo, lie down as if dead and relax your vigilence&quot; is one place I have been, but need to visit many, many, more times. <br><br>
The process you relate is one of a meditative connection with life, spiritualty, and the underlying processes within us all. Unfortunately for some, such meditation is one of disconnection and escape. This distinction must be clearly understood. <br><br>
I will study your words carefully.<br><br>
Hecito yelo, my Brother.   
<p><code>--   (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


